==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*kar-'', perhaps from the same Indo-European root as Latin [[garrire]] ‘chatter’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[kara]], Old High German [[chara]] ‘grief’, Old Norse {{Latinx|[[kǫr]]}} ‘sickbed’, Gothic [[𐌺𐌰𐍂𐌰]].  Related to [[cearig|ċeariġ]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'kæaɹʊ/}}

===Noun===
'''cearu''' ''f''
# [[suffering]], [[sorrow]], [[grief]]
#:''Ic sceolde ana mine ceare cwiðan'': I must speak my suffering alone.
# [[anxiety]]
# [[care]], [[caution]]
#:''Cearu wæs geniwod geworden in wicum'': care had been renewed in the dwellings.  (''Beowulf'')

